				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Why on earth would you have multiple input routines? The normal is to read all the bits from the joypad and put them in a byte, since, conveniently enough, there are exactly 8 buttons in a NES controller. This routine is always the same, but each "game state" will read this byte and do different things based on its contents.
<br />
<br />Unless you are confused by those awkward demos where the programmer branches to different action immediately after reading the bit from the controller register... is that it? That is an awful way to control games. You'd better just stuff the input into a byte (for each controller) and use that to make decisions.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

